==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈbændən/}}
* {{audio|en-us-abandon.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|abandoner|lang=fro}}, formed from {{term|a|lang=fro}} + {{term|bandon||jurisdiction, control|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|bannum||proclamation|lang=la}}, of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|frk}} ''*ban'', from {{proto|Germanic|bannanan|to proclaim, command|lang=en}} (compare {{etyl|en|-}} {{term|ban|lang=en}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|bʰeh₂-||bʰa-|to speak|lang=en}}. Displaced {{etyl|enm|-}} ''[[forleten#Middle English|forleten]]'' "to abandon" (from {{etyl|ang|-}} ''[[forlætan#Old English|forlǣtan]]'', ''[[anforlætan#Old English|anforlǣtan]]'') and {{etyl|enm|-}} ''[[forleven#Middle English|forleven]]'' "to leave behind, abandon" (from {{etyl|ang|-}} ''[[forlæfan#Old English|forlǣfan]]'').

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To [[give up]] control of, to [[surrender]].
#* {{rfdate}} I. Taylor:
#*: Hope was overthrown, yet could not be '''abandoned'''.
# {{transitive}} To leave behind, to [[desert]].
#: ''Many baby girls have been '''abandoned''' on the streets of Beijing everyday.''
# {{transitive|obsolete}} To [[cast out|cast]] or [[drive out]]; to [[banish]]; to [[expel]]; to [[reject]].
#* '''1594''', [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''The Taming of the Shrew'', act I, scene ii:
#*: Being all this time '''abandoned''' from your bed.
# {{transitive}} To [[relinquish]] a [[claim]] to [[property]] to [[underwriter]]s.

