==English==
{{slim-wikipedia}}
{{wikisource1911Enc|Abduction|Abduction (law)}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|abductio|abductiō|robbing; abduction|lang=la}}, from {{term|abduco|abdūcō|take or lead away|lang=la}}. Compare French {{term|lang=fr|abduction}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|/əbˈdʌk.ʃən/}}, {{SAMPA|/@b"dVk.S@n/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈdʌk.ʃən/}}, {{SAMPA|/{b"dVk.S@n/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act of [[abduce|abducing]] or [[abduct]]ing; a [[draw]]ing apart; a [[carry]]ing away. {{rfex}}
# {{physiology}} The [[movement]] which [[separate]]s a [[limb]] or other part from the [[axis]], or middle line, of the body.
# {{legal}} The [[wrongful]], and usually the [[forcible]], [[carry off|carrying off]] of a human being.
#: ''the '''abduction''' of a child''
# {{logic}} A [[syllogism]] or form of [[argument]] in which the [[major]] is [[evident]], but the minor is only [[probable]].
#* '''2005''', Ronnie Cann, Ruth Kempson, Lutz Marten, ''The Dynamics of Language, an Introduction'', page 256:
#*: The significance of such a step is that it is not morphologically triggered: it is a step of '''abduction''', and what is required here is a meta-level process of reasoning.

====Usage notes====
* In Gregg shorthand (version: [[w:Gregg_Shorthand#Centennial_Gregg_Shorthand|Centennial]], [[w:Gregg_Shorthand#Series_90_Gregg_Shorthand|Series 90]], [[w:Gregg_Shorthand#Diamond_Jubilee_Gregg_Shorthand|DJS]], [[w:Gregg_Shorthand#Simplified_Gregg_Shorthand|Simplified]], [[w:Gregg_Shorthand#Anniversary_Gregg_Shorthand|Anniversary]], [[w:Gregg_Shorthand#Pre-Anniversary_Gregg_Shorthand|Pre-Anniversary]]) the word is represented: a - b - d - u - k - sh

====Synonyms====
* {{sense|legal|carrying off of human being}} [[kidnapping]]
* {{sense|logic}} [[retroduction]]
* {{sense|determining most plausible explanation}} [[retroduction]]

