==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|abetten|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|abeter|lang=fro}}, from {{term|a-|lang=fro}} + {{term|beter||to bait an animal|lang=fro}}, of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|non}} {{term|beita||to cause to bite, bait, incite|lang=non}}, from {{proto|Germanic|baitijanan|to cause to bite|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|bheid-|to split|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|beita||to set dogs on", "to feed|lang=is}}. 

Alternate etymology traces the Middle English and Old French words through {{etyl|ang|-}} *{{term||ābǣtan|sc=Latinx|to hound on|lang=ang}}, from {{term|a-|ā-|lang=ang}} + {{term|bætan|bǣtan|sc=Latinx|to bait|lang=ang}}, from the same {{proto|Germanic}} source.

See also {{term|bait}}, {{term|bet}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/əˈbɛt/}}
* {{audio|En-us-abet.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɛt}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abet|t|ing}}

# {{transitive}} To [[assist]] or [[encourage]] by aid or [[countenance]], especially in crime.
#* '''1823''', Ringan Gilhaize, ''The covenanters, by the author of Annals of the parish'':
#*: Those who would exalt themselves by '''abetting''' the strength of the Godless, and the wrength of the oppressors.
# {{transitive|obsolete|_|except negatively}} To support, countenance, maintain, [[uphold]], or aid any cause, opinion, or action; to maintain.
# {{transitive}} To support, [[uphold]], or aid; to maintain.
#* '''1835''', Jeremy Taylor, George Rust, ''The whole works of the Right Rev. Jeremy Taylor'':
#*: Our duty is urged, and our confidence '''abetted'''.
# {{obsolete}} To [[urge]] on, [[stimulate]] (a person to do something) - first known use 1390
# {{obsolete}} To back up one's forecast of a doubtful issue, by staking money, etc., to [[bet]].

====Quotations====
* {{seeCites}}

