==English==
{{Webster 1913}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|abhorrens|abhorrēns|lang=la}}, present active participle of {{term|abhorreo|abhorreō|abhor|lang=la}}.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# [[abhor|Abhorring]]; [[detesting]]; having or showing [[abhorrence]]; [[loathing]]; hence, strongly opposed to; as, ''abhorrent'' thoughts.
#* {{quote-book|year=1803|author=Edmund Burke|passage=The persons most '''abhorrent''' from blood, and treason, and arbitrary confiscation, might remain silent spectators of this civil war between the vices.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=99gcAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22The%20persons%20most%20abhorrent%20from%20blood%20and%20treason%22&pg=PA248#v=onepage&f=false}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1822|author=Richard Clover|title=Leonidas|passage=The arts of pleasure in despotic courts I spurn, '''abhorrent'''; in a spotless heart I look for pleasure.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=DbEDAAAAQAAJ&dq=The%20arts%20of%20pleasure%20in%20despotic%20courts%20I%20spurn%20abhorrent&pg=PA205#v=onepage&f=false}}
# Contrary or [[repugnant]]; [[discordant]]; [[inconsistent]]; -- followed by ''to''.
#* {{quote-book|year=1827|author=[[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]|title=The History of the Decline And Fall of the Roman Empire
|passage=This legal, and, as it should seem, injudicious profanation, so '''abhorrent''' to out stricter principles, was received with a very faint murmur, ... |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rwoMAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Injudicious%20profanation%2C%20so%20abhorrent%20to%20our%20stricter%20principles.%22&pg=PA82#v=onepage&f=false}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1990|author=James Hankins|title=Plato in the Italian Renaissance|passage=In establishing his ideal state he expressed some opinions utterly abhorrent to our customs and ways of living. He believed, for instance, that all wives should be held in common ... with the result that no one could tell his own children from those of a perfect stranger.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=BLgfAAAAIAAJ&lpg=PA65&dq=abhorrent&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q=abhorrent&f=false}}
# [[detestable|Detestable]]
#* {{quote-book|year=1833|author=[[w:Isaac Taylor|Isaac Taylor]]|title=Fanaticism|passage=If Pride, '''abhorrent''' as it is, and if Ambition, ...|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uX0NAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Pride%2C%20abhorrent'%20as%20it%20is%22&pg=PA3#v=onepage&q&f=false}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1936|title=On Being Human|author=Paul E. More|passage=That, I protest, is a doctrine psychologically impossible and ethically '''abhorrent'''.|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=qRDpbuo8t14C&lpg=PA181&dq=abhorrent&pg=PA181#v=onepage&q&f=false}}

