==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|lang=fro|abominable}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|abominabilis|abōminābilis|deserving abhorrence|lang=la}}, from {{term|abominor|abōminor|abhor, deprecate as an ill omen|lang=la}}, from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{term|ominor|ōminor|forebode, predict, presage|lang=la}}, from {{term|omen|ōmen|sign, token, omen|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-abominable.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Worthy of, or causing, [[abhorrence]], as a thing of evil omen; [[odious]] in the [[utmost]] degree; very [[hateful]]; [[detestable]]; [[loathsome]]; [[execrable]].
# {{obsolete}} Excessive; large; -- used as an [[intensive]].
#: '''''Note:''''' {{w|Juliana Berners}} ... [[informs]] us that in her time (15th century), "'''abomynable''' syght of monkes" was elegant English for "a large company of friars". - {{w|George Perkins Marsh}}
# Very [[bad]] or [[inferior]].

====Usage notes====
* Nouns to which "abominable" is often applied: man, woman, crime, act, deed, sin, vice, character, place, mystery<!--because of Darwin?-->, treatment, church.

