==English== {{wikipedia}}
===Etymology=== [[magical|Magical]] word used in certain [[Gnostic]] writings, relation to [[Greek]] [[abraxas|Abraxas]], a Gnostic [[deity]].
It may also be a corruption of the {{etyl|arc}} term {{term|עבדא כד ברא|עַבְדָא כְּדַ ברָא|lang=arc|sc=Hebr}}, ''avda ked vara''; “what was said has been done”; or perhaps, {{etyl|he}} {{term|עבראכדברא|lang=he|sc=Hebr}}, ''avra kedavra''; “what has said has come to pass.”
It may also be the combination of three {{etyl|he}} words {{term|ארבע-אחד-ארבע|lang=he|sc=Hebr}} when it is read from right to left [http://www.scribd.com/doc/14656725/Abracadabra] .
The Aramaic is the source of the ''Avada Kedavra'' killing curse in the ''Harry Potter'' books.<!-- JK Rowling said this 15 April 2004, at the Edinburgh Book Festival, but referred to the meaning as “let the thing be destroyed”-->
===Pronunciation=== * {{audio|en-us-abracadabra.ogg|Audio (US)}}
===Interjection=== {{en-interj|pos=abracadabra!}}
# Used to [[indicate]] that a [[magic trick]] or other [[illusion]] has been [[perform]]ed.
====Translations==== {{trans-top|used to indicate that a magic trick or other illusion has been performed}} * Czech: {{t-|cs|abrakadabra}} * Finnish: {{t|fi|abrakadabra}} * Polish: {{t|pl|abrakadabra}} * Portuguese: {{t-|pt|abracadabra}} {{trans-mid}} * Russian: {{t|ru|абракадабра|f|tr=abrakadábra|sc=Cyrl}} * Serbian: {{t+|sr|абракадабра|tr=abrakadabra|sc=Cyrl}} * Swedish: {{t|sv|abrakadabra}}, {{t|sv|abra kadabra}} * Turkish: {{t|tr|abrakadabra}} {{trans-bottom}}
===Noun=== {{en-noun|-}}
# A [[mystical]] word or [[collocation]] of letters from [[kabbalism]]. # Complicated [[technicality|technicalities]], [[jargon]] that one does not understand much if at all. #: ''I don’t know all the theoretical '''abracadabra''' about how it works, I’m only its pilot.''
====Translations==== <!-- need tables --> {{checktrans}} * {{ttbc|vi}}: [[câu thần chú]], [[lời nói khó hiểu]]
[[Category:en:Magic words]]
----
