==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|abruptus|lang=la}}, perfect passive participle of {{term|abrumpo|abrumpō|break off|lang=la}}, formed from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{term|rumpo|rumpō|break|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|En-us-abrupt.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|'''more abrupt''' or [[abrupter]]|'''most abrupt''' or [[abruptest]]}}

# Extremely [[steep]] or [[craggy]] as if broken up; [[precipitous]].
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Thomson]]
#*: ''Tumbling through ricks '''abrupt'''.''
# Without notice to prepare the mind for the event; [[sudden]]; [[hasty]]; [[unceremonious]].
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''Henry VI Part I, II-iii''
#*: ''The cause of your '''abrupt''' departure.''
# [[curt|Curt]] in manner; [[rude]]; [[uncivil]]; [[impolite]].
# Having sudden [[transitions]] from one subject or state to another; [[unconnected]].
#: ''The party came to an '''abrupt''' end when the parents of our host arrived.''
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Ben Jonson|Ben Jonson]]
#: ''The '''abrupt''' style, which hath many breaches.''
# {{botany}} Suddenly [[terminating]], as if [[cut off]]; [[truncate]].

====Synonyms====
* {{sense|precipitous}} [[broken]], [[rough]], [[rugged]]
* {{sense|without time to prepare}} [[brusque]], [[sudden]]
* {{sense|uncivil}}[[blunt]], [[brusque]]
* {{sense|without transition}} [[disconnected]], [[unexpected]]

